Ssh key pair..Â ï¿½

1. Update System Packages
sudo apt update

2. Install OpenSSH Server
sudo apt install -y openssh-server

3. Check SSH Service Status
sudo systemctl status ssh

4. Install SSH Client (optional)
sudo apt install -y openssh-client

5. Backup SSH Configuration File
sudo cp /etc/ssh/sshd_config /etc/ssh/sshd_config.original
sudo chmod a-w /etc/ssh/sshd_config.original

6. Edit SSH Configuration
sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config
PubkeyAuthentication yes
PasswordAuthentication yes
ChallengeResponseAuthentication no

7. Test SSH Configuration
sudo sshd -t -f /etc/ssh/sshd_config

8. Restart SSH Service
sudo systemctl restart ssh

9. Generate SSH Key Pair
ssh-keygen -t ed25519
10. Copy Public Key to Remote Host
ssh-copy-id sethu@10.0.2.15

11. Connect to Remote Server
ssh sethu@10.0.2.15

12. Message is stored here
sudo nano /etc/issue.net

13. Change PasswordAuthentication setting
sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config
PasswordAuthentication No

Firewall Configuration
1. Install UFW Firewall
sudo apt install ufw -y

2. Enable UFW
sudo ufw enable

3. Check Firewall Status
sudo ufw status

4. Optional: Add Custom SSH Login Message
sudo nano /etc/issue.net

5. Restart SSH
sudo systemctl restart ssh

Two-Step Authentication (Google Authenticator)
1. Install Google Authenticator PAM Module
sudo apt install libpam-google-authenticator -y

2. Run Google Authenticator Setup
google-authenticator

3. Restart SSH After Configuration
sudo systemctl restart ssh
sudo journalctlÂ -fuÂ ssh.service


